description.text:
IF YOU HAVE DOWNLOADED THESE FILES BEFORE, I STRONGLY SUGGEST YOU DELETE THEM, RE-DOWNLOAD THIS, AND ONLY USE THE "REV.2" FILES

It's worth mentioning this is considered a "low-poly" version of the Mida from Destiny 1, It does not have all the high detail nuts, bolts, and switches seen on high def images of the mida.

I may rework some files into a more Destiny 2 version of the rifle if I have time/motivation. (they changed several details and the clip shape)

If something needs changing please let me know!

I have finished printing my own Mida and added all new REV.2 files that SHOULD fix all the major reworking I needed to do, there may be some issues still that I missed so let me know if you discover a fitting issue.

The majority of the changes I've made from the original are orientation, cutting large parts in half, and reducing the number of parts that need supports. Along with a few flusher fitting adjustments as I make my own and find it needs post-production fitting.

I've only kept the old and in-process files in case someone was using them. I intend to delete them in a month or so and only keep the REV.2 files.

I printed mine successfully on a Airwolf AW3D HD printer in ABS. this is a 200x300x300 print area, and every piece easily fits inside this printer! 1.0 wall thickness

If you have issues with any parts or questions/concerns, please let me know and I'll make the corrections as soon as I can!

as always of course, all rights to go Bungie and Destiny/destiny 2. I've thoroughly enjoyed Destiny 2 on PS4 and looking forward to the PC release!

UPDATE LOG:
10/6/17

  • Added a "hinged" laser sight, which should allow it to flip out instead of being fixed.

10/10/17

  • Found an issue with the Thumbstock alignment not meeting the stock body correctly.
  • Set thing as "In progress" till I complete my own and adjust any issues and errors I find along the way!
  • Added REV.02 rear sock body 1&2 to address flusher fit
  • Added REV.02 mainbody rear (fits on top of thumbstock by rear stock) Adjusted fit and detail.
  • Added Center Mainbody (part that goes on/above thumbstock) to fit better, and hopefully print easier (EDIT: Found issue with fit, will update once replacement is confirmed)
    -Removed original files to reduce confusion with duplicates

10/11/17
-Added Mag left & right, as i don't know why I had it sliced differently than everything else.

10/16/17

  • Found some issues with the center main body part. will release new versions soon.
  • Updated Tabs (a detail part) to be a little higher definition

10/18/17

  • Replaced stock shroud with one that was slightly edited to not need support for a tiny lip. making it easier to print.
  • Updated folding laser sight to one without a graphic error.

10/19/17

  • Added Rev.2.01 of the Handle and main body that combine them for best fit and easier assembly. It has a left, right, and (2)center pieces.
  • Alternatively added Handle parts REV.04 which has cutouts that should match the previous center body part.

10/26/17

  • Nearly completed assembly, discovered a alignment issue that goes way back to how the stock rear meets the entire upper half. will need to adjust several pieces to make it work correctly. Once the rifle is finished I'll release a updated version of EVERY SINGLE PART. that I know fit together the way it should. there are numerous parts that fit odd or need work to fit the way it should. so the newest revision I'll release SHOULD fix all of those that I had troubles with, in a easy to print format! When I release this, I would suggest EVERYONE who is printing or saved the current files, to use the latest. and the latest files will NOT necessarily be comparable with the old parts.

10/30/17

I FINISHED PRINTING FINALLY!!!
this took an entire spool +extra (because of re-prints) of 3mm ABS.

I added all new REV.2 files for ALL the latest files and changes I made. It's about 90% good. there will be some post-editing needed for everything to fit as well as you'd like, but it's better than the original files for printing this guy out.
Everything I printed I setup to be able to print in a 200x300 print area.

title: Open XY blocks with adjustable belt tension - for original Ultimaker (8mm gantry rods)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
These blocks can be replaced without having to dismantle the rods and pulleys, after of course removing the original blocks. The belt tension is adjustable through a banana cam. The gantry can be easily removed without undoing the blocks.  
The 6mm gantry rod version will be posted soon.

Print all parts with 0.1mm layer and 100% infill.
Required parts for each block:
6x M3 M6mm socket bolt
5x M3 nut
1x M3 square nut
2x tube (3mm inside, 6.3mm outside diameter, 6.5mm length) plastic or metal. I used cuts from my old Bowden tube. Make sure you have all parts ready before dismantling the gantry, rods and pulleys! Assembly:
Re-assemble the rods, belts and pulleys as normal without the blocks, just the brass journal bearings in place. Don't tighten the sync pulleys, but tighten the driving ones (motors).
Place blocks on the rods and assemble the key wedges, don't tighten. Slide in place the blocks over the journal bearings. slightly tighten the bolt.
One block at a time:
Place the square nut in its captive location.
Screw the bolt few threads through the square nut.
Slide the banana in place.
Capture the belt under the hinge screws passing through the tube cuts acting as rollers.
Position the gantry and secure rods on the blocks using the brackets. Gently tighten bolts.
Tighten the belts using the adjusting bolts, enough to remove slack and hear the belt give a tone. You can balance all belts to give the same tone. Don't over-tighten!
Square the gantry and tighten the pulleys. You may want to use a thread locking compound like Loctite Blue. Remember that to untighten later, you will have to heat the grubscrews or use acetone to dissolve the thread lock. Level the platform and start printing. Enjoy! If you like this design, feel free to donate and ask for improvements:

title: MakerGear M2 Printer Spool Holder -- 3/4" End Caps

description.text: The filament spool mount on the MakerGear M2 works great -- if you have the thick-edge spools like MakerGear uses. For other spools, the mod suggested by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:37210 works way better (and both can be mounted simultaneously for easy switching). Unfortunately, MatterHackers and some other filament vendors often use spools that have very small core holes, and the rod suggested by Thing 37210 will not fit through.... This is a simple push-on end cap with an interior designed to firmly grip a standard 3/4" wooden dowel as shown. Without these silly little end caps, the uneven winding of some spools can cause the dowel to walk out of the spool... which would be bad.

Start by making most of Thing 37210, then make this end cap instead of the one in Thing 37210.  
This end cap is an easy print in ABS or PLA. The "M2" label is at the top while printing, which leaves a span, but any mess will be hidden because the span is inside the end cap. You need 2: one for each end of the dowel. They don't get glued on because you need to take one off to pass the dowel through the center of the spool.  
Incidentally, the 3/4" dowel should be about 8" long.

title: Baseplate for Flirc Gen 2 Raspberry Pi3 Case

description.text:
This is an optional baseplate for use with the great updated Gen 2 Raspberry Pi3 case provided by Flirc. This baseplate includes tabs for mounting the case onto a wall or other surface. 3.6mm thick spacers are included and can be used to raise the case off the mounting surface. A hexagon hole pattern is used to improve airflow into the bottom of the case. The mounting holes are spaced at 80mm in the longer axis and 75.5mm in the shorter axis.

This baseplate offers the same GPIO cable access, LED access, and recessed mounting screw holes as the OEM baseplate from Flirc. Access to the micro SD card is similar, but for printability reasons isn't as elaborate as on the injection-molded OEM baseplate.

Note that this baseplate has only been tested with a Raspberry Pi3 and the Gen 2 case from Flirc. Compatibility with other versions of the Raspberry Pi or with the original case from Flirc is unknown.

Printer:

MakerFarm 200mm i3v

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.20mm layer

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Tested on a highly customized MakerFarm i3v printer running Smoothieware and Simplify3D v3 as the slicer.

Support structure will likely have to be added during slicing under the brace that extends across the SD-card slot. Supports may also need to added in each of the recessed holes for the case screws for the recesses to print cleanly.

There isn't a lot of infill volume. My typical 30% infill seemed to work fine.

Check hole sizes and test fit the baseplate with a Raspberry Pi3 before assembling the baseplate onto a case. Check for adequate clearance between the baseplate and SD-card. File any burrs from support structure or sagging portions of the baseplate brace as required.

Glue the spacers onto the bottom of the mounting tabs if desired to keep them in place.

UPDATE 3: I have changed the pegs and holes. Now the doors have the pegs and the frame has the holes. Let's see if this time they work. Also, I have made the doors slightly smaller to give them more space to swing.

UPDATE 2: I have re scaled the doors a little to make them match the board better, but they are still Massive ;). I have also moved the pegs towards the center to try to make them more more "openable". Again, could not test them as my printer is still dead.

UPDATE 1: I have scaled down the pegs in the frames. Now they should fit better into the door holes, but again no printer, no testing.

Hello everyone! Since I'm a Massive Darkness player I thought it would be nice to have some thick fat massive doors. Like real dungeon doors that should keep monsters at bay. So Here is my take on them, inspired in the doors seen in the Elder Scrolls franchise.

For the door frame I have remixed one of the Zombicide Doors frame from Isolt, the rest is all original. Mind that they are almost 9cm long x 5 cm tall, real dungeon doors. But if you want them smaller they are easily scalable.

They are not tested yet, as my printer is out of service at the moment, so any feedback will be welcome!

Enjoy!!!

description.text:
M2.5 x 6 screws can be expensive and difficult to find:

Thanks to 3D design software and 3D printing, you can now print out small, inexpensive objects. These pins or pegs, were designed to act as fasteners for the Pi computer to a case that I found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:922740

However, they could be modified to work with a case of choice or for various other projects that require small fasteners. The pins rely on friction to secure the computer to the case and are not threaded, though it should be noted that thread-like grooves are produced during the printing process. In the pictures provided with this project, you will notice that the pins have not been pushed flush with the computer board, and this is due to the fact that they can be very difficult to remove once they are fully inserted into the mounting holes.

Enjoy, comment, and share!

description.text:
DecoTime is my Art Deco styled timer. It is powered by an Arduino driving two x27 168 or switec X25 stepper motors moving the needles. It also uses a MCP23S17 to drive the LEDs and take input from the two rotary encoders. A solenoid rings the bell when finished and the top LED flashes. It can be run off batteries(alkaline or NiMh), or usb. It also has an expansion port to use I2C with power. You can find the knobs, battery pack, and needles in my other uploads on thingiverse.

You can read all about it in great detail on my website, including schematics and directions.
http://coolate.com/blog/coolate-pages/deco-time-angular-timer/

I printed the parts on an ultimaker, seeMeCNC and an old makerbot. The two main parts require supports, and should be printed inside down toward the plate. I used PLA, and coated some parts in XTC to make them shine.

ALL the design work was done in tinkercad, and are public if you want to fiddle with it.

description.text:
Public Domain Modulus Gear OpenSCAD code
version 1.0
This code defines a gear based on its modulus rather than pitch in mm, Modulus is the ration of tooth count:diameter, effectively the pitch of the gear is modulus * pi, ie, a gear of mod=1 has a tooth pitch of 3.1514mm.

The advantage of using modulus rather than pitch to define a gear is that it is very easy to prototype - for example, a gear of mod = 1 will have a diameter that matches the tooth count, with mod = 2, radius = tooth count.

This code is based on the poblic domain Parametric Involute Spur Gear code by Leemon Baird found at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5505

The file here is designed as both a library file (just use include at the start of your own OpenSCAD file, after removing the modgear call), and as a customizer so you can create and download your own custom gears directly from Thingiverse!

Note: If using the options of a square or hexagonal center hole, be aware that the size is diagonal (corner to corner) not the side length. This, for a square bore 4 mm an a side, the hole size should be set to 5.7 mm (This requires applying the Pythagorean theorem).

title: Philips Diamond Clean toothbrush  wall mount

description.text:
A wall mount for the Philips Sonicare Diamond Clean toothbrush. No need of drilling holes into the plates - use silicon to attach the stand to the plates. Special network of channels in the mount body allows the silicon to hold very strong to the printed PLA body. I already printed similar wall mount for Oral B and it was really hard to remove it - so there is zero chance the mount to unglue and fall down accidentally.

Before gluing the mount to the ceramic plates - clean the surface with alcohol. Then apply an even layer of silicon and press gently the mount until the silicon squeezes away from the side holes. Remove the excessive silicon (use a cloth with soap) and fix the mount for couple of hours with paper tape. After the silicon settles down - remove the paper tape and insert the charger, it should fit and snap into the hole.

Ideally the silicon color should be the same as the gap between the plates (transparent silicon leaves the side channels of the base visible). The filament color should be chosen according to the plates. I achieved the best 3D printing results by placing the hole for the charger on the 3D printer plate - some more filament is used for supports but the surface finish is the best.

description.text:
The Garage Door Monitor continously monitors whether your garage door is closed, and sends out an email or text message if it has been left open for more than 15 minutes. It uses the popular ESP8266 WiFi module, and relays messages to you via the IFTTT web service. In our household, we have accidentally left the garage door open on multiple occasions, and this device has saved our bacon more than once.

The source code and detailed assembly instructions can be found at my GitHub website: https://github.com/elkayem/GarageDoorMonitor

Features:

  • Email and/or text sent every 15 minutes when your door has been left open, notifying you what time it was opened and how long
  • Email/text sent once your door has been closed
  • Synchronization with NIST time
  • Enable/disable button, which can temporarily disable the monitor
  • RGB LED indicating monitor status
  • (Optional) logging of door status via Adafruit IO
  • (Optional) OLED Display

The following parts are required, as pictured below:

  • NodeMCU V1.0 development board (sometimes also listed as v2 at online shops such as eBay or AliExpress)
  • Normally Open magnetic switch
  • (2) Female headers
  • Common Anode RGB LED
  • Screw Terminal Block (2 pin 3.5mm Pitch)
  • 6x6mm tactile button
  • (3) 300 Ohm resistors
  • (Optional) 4-pin male header
  • (Optional) Printed Circuit Board (See GitHub site for Eagle files)
  • (Optional) 128x64 I2C OLED Display (Preferably a two-color display, e.g., yellow/blue)

The PCB is indicated as optional, since the circuit is simple enough to hand solder on a PCB breadboard if desired (See GitHub for schematic). An OLED display can enhance the monitor, but is not necessary.

title: Age of Sigmar Base Conversion - Warhammer Fantasy
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
I have a bunch of Warhammer Fantasy figures and my friends started playing Age of Sigmar. While someday I will have the perfect army, the idea of migrating all of my Orcs and Goblins from their square bases to their round and oval bases sounds overwhelming at this moment. So I decided to try something else - a wrapper around the square bases that creates a circular / oval base. Not perfect, as the square base still protrudes outside of the circle / oval by a bit. However, I think it works well enough to give it a try. Right now, the distances are measured from the unit features to the other unit features, but some people play with the house rule of from base to base. In that case, having a base very similar to the other people may be beneficial. If you print in PETG or PLA it provides a nice snug fit that doesn't allow it to fall out during game play.

As an added benefit, I can print in different colors and differentiate among different units. Otherwise, it is easy to confuse the 30 orcs in one unit with the 30 orcs in the other unit.

While a search on Thingiverse reveals that at least someone else tried this, I like to make things highly customizable. I have included the OpenSCAD file that you can use to create the other bases. There are two reference lists on the internet that may help:
Holy War and Google Docs.

Feel free to print your own. If you want me to print them out, check out my Etsy store.

This is a replacement foot pad for furniture. I had a reclining sofa that had some foot pads on it that wore out do to being a little bit weak in design so I decided to printed some new ones and this is what I made.

I printed mine with 100% infill to make them stronger than the originals. I used ABS as it is what I had but other types of filament should work just as well just as long as they are strong enough once printed. Just remember that this will have weight on them if used so I recommend that you print them with 100% Solid Infill.

Also I just thought of this as I was typing this up. I am not sure of all the attributes of all the filaments but if there is any that will leave marks on things when rubbed on them, then I would suggest not using that type of filament when making these. Just encase you use them on a hardwood or tile floor. I am not sure if there is any filament that does that but just encase I think I should mention it. No need to mark up your floors. ;)

Note on Supplied Files:
Besides supplying the (.STL) I also supplied the Google SketchUp (.SKP) file so you it can be modified if need be. I am currently using SketchUp 2017. Dimensions of the part are in the (.SKP) but I will explain them a little below.

Note on the Dimensions:
The part is 11.6mm in height and 30.5mm in diameter.
The hole for the bolt is 8mm in diameter. The space for the Bolt Head is 18mm in diameter and 8mm in depth. This allows 3.6mm of solid support between the Bolt Head and the furniture it will be attached to.

title: Mosaic Palette Scroll Wheel Connector Clamp

description.text:
If you have experienced the scroll wheel connector working it's way loose mid-print then you will know the frsutration this causes. The Palette is unable to recover and requires a reset meaning your print is completely lost and you have to start again.

This clamp attaches to the Palette using the existing 2 bolts used to connect the female connector within the chassis. To fit, simply remove the top cover, undo the 2 bolts holding the connector, being careful not to lose the 2 nuts on the inside of the chassis, feed the bolts through the holes in the clamp and reassemble.

Ensure you fit with the Palette logo facing uppermost. This is because there is a small recess inside the clamp to accept the nib on the black connector.

The bolts are long enough to accept the clamp so no additional parts are required.

TIP: To make things easier if you dab the outside of each nut with a spot of superglue before you remove the bolts then they will remian in place and cannot fall into the lower cavity.

Cheers
